{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01N7a3aYqb1J5RwgBBnjEN52","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. I need to:\n\n1. Set up kubectl to use the proxy at 127.0.0.1:38745\n2. Rotate the HTTP CA and leaf certificates for the Elasticsearch cluster in the `elasticsearch` namespace\n3. The relevant parameters are:\n   - `BENCH_PARAM_TLS_SECRET_NAME`: `es-http-tls`\n   - `BENCH_PARAM_HTTP_CA_CONFIGMAP_NAME`: `es-http-ca`\n   - `BENCH_PARAM_OLD_FINGERPRINT_CONFIGMAP_NAME`: `es-http-old`\n   - `BENCH_PARAM_HTTP_SERVICE_NAME`: `es-http`\n   - `BENCH_PARAM_CLUSTER_PREFIX`: `es-cluster`\n\nI've already verified that 5 pods are running in the `elasticsearch` namespace and saved the old CA and leaf fingerprints to the `es-http-old` configmap. Now I need to rotate the HTTP CA and leaf certificates while keeping downtime minimal.\n\nThe constraints are that there's no ECK operator, the new certs will be valid for about a year, and clients can trust the new CA. My strategy is to use a bundling approach: I'll generate a new self-signed CA and leaf certificate, then add the new CA to the trust bundle while the old certs are still active, switch over to the new certs, and finally remove the old CA from the bundle.\n\nLet me start by setting up the kubeconfig and checking the current state of the cluster.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":651,"cache_read_input_tokens":31458,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":651},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"74c2cc84-754d-4db6-921e-d8fedf78493f","uuid":"9af450bd-8898-4c5d-b5bb-b19e0c9bc875","request_id":"req_011Ccetm1vadX7TVHZsrcAHd"}
